{
  "id": "8a219508-f841-4c2c-8ad7-b00ef6c1502b",
  "slug": "insurance-bad-faith-notice-drafting",
  "name": "Insurance Bad Faith Notice (Time-Limited Demand)",
  "summary": "This skill guides an LLM to draft a time-limited policy-limits settlement demand designed to create a clean evidentiary record of a reasonable opportunity to settle and to trigger the insurer's duty of good faith toward its insured. It covers jurisdiction-specific verification of bad faith prerequisites (including statutory notice requirements), a documented liability and damages narrative establishing excess exposure, unambiguous and operationally practical acceptance mechanics, defensible deadlines, and professionally calibrated bad faith warnings. The workflow embeds ethical guardrails under the ABA Model Rules, mandatory anti-hallucination requirements for legal citations, and a rigorous quality review framework focused on adversarial resilience and later judicial scrutiny.",
  "content": "# Insurance Bad Faith Notice (Time-Limited Demand)\n\n## 1. Opening Context\n\nThis skill produces a time-limited policy-limits settlement demand letter\u2014often called a \"bad faith setup\" demand, a \"Stowers demand\" (in Texas), or simply a \"policy limit demand\"\u2014directed to a liability insurer. In competent plaintiff-side practice, a properly constructed time-limited demand crystallizes the insurer's opportunity to settle within limits, creates a clean record of reasonableness and cooperation by the claimant, and positions the case for an extra-contractual bad faith claim if the insurer unreasonably fails to accept and an excess judgment results. The letter is not merely \"tough\" language; it is a disciplined evidentiary record designed to survive later scrutiny by claims management, coverage counsel, a trial court on summary judgment, and potentially an appellate court evaluating the insurer's claims-handling conduct.\n\nDone poorly, this workflow can backfire. Overreaching deadlines, ambiguous acceptance terms, missing documentation, or \"gotcha\" conditions allow the insurer to argue it lacked a fair opportunity to settle, that the demand was not reasonable, that the claimant impeded settlement, or that acceptance was impossible within the time allowed\u2014undermining the very bad faith theory the letter is meant to preserve. Professional standards for this work product include competence and diligence (ABA Model Rules 1.1 and 1.3), truthful and non-misleading communication (Model Rule 4.1), avoidance of means that have no substantial purpose other than to embarrass, delay, or burden a third person (Model Rule 4.4), and protection of client confidences (Model Rule 1.6). The letter must also be drafted with the awareness that it is likely to become an exhibit in later litigation, meaning every sentence should be defensible under oath.\n\n## 2. Understanding the Context and Purpose\n\nThe time-limited demand exists at the intersection of contract law (the insurance policy) and tort law (the bad faith claim). An insurance company has a fiduciary-like duty to protect its insured. This duty includes an obligation to settle a claim when it is possible to do so within policy limits and where a reasonable insurer would do so to avoid the risk of a judgment exceeding those limits. This principle is rooted in foundational cases such as *G.A. Stowers Furniture Co. v. American Indemnity Co.*, 15 S.W.2d 544 (Tex. Comm'n App. 1929) (Texas); *Comunale v. Traders & General Insurance Co.*, 50 Cal. 2d 654 (1958) (California); and *Holt v. Aetna Casualty & Surety Co.*, 189 Ga. App. 827 (1989) (Georgia). Each state's doctrinal framework varies, but the common thread is that an insurer must give at least as much consideration to the insured's interests as it does to its own financial interests when evaluating settlement.\n\nBefore suit\u2014or during early litigation when liability and damages are sufficiently clear\u2014the claimant communicates a firm opportunity: pay limits (or an agreed amount) by a date certain under defined acceptance terms, in exchange for a release that protects the insured from personal exposure. The demand letter is designed to establish that (a) the insurer knew or should have known liability exposure was significant, (b) damages reasonably threatened an excess verdict, (c) policy limits were an objectively reasonable settlement figure, (d) the claimant made a clear offer capable of prompt acceptance, and (e) the insurer failed to accept without a reasonable basis.\n\nThe primary audience is the claims adjuster and claims supervisor, but you should draft as if a coverage and bad faith litigator and a judge will read it later line by line. The letter must therefore be unambiguous, internally consistent, and anchored in concrete facts: a liability narrative, a damages summary, documented specials, and the settlement mechanics needed to close. Strategically, you want to remove excuses for delay (missing medical authorizations, unclear lien status, uncertain identities of insureds, unclear policy limits, unclear release scope) while still imposing a credible deadline that creates urgency and forces escalation within the insurer's claims hierarchy.\n\nThis skill instructs the LLM to (i) identify the governing jurisdiction and forum, (ii) verify any jurisdiction-specific prerequisites by web research, and (iii) flag open legal questions for attorney review. Because of significant state-to-state variation in bad faith doctrine\u2014some states impose statutory prerequisites such as civil remedy notices before statutory bad faith suits, others rely primarily on common law duties, and some treat claimant-created deadlines skeptically if they appear designed to manufacture bad faith rather than to settle\u2014this jurisdictional verification step is non-negotiable.\n\n## 3. Prerequisites and Information Gathering\n\nBefore drafting, the LLM must determine the governing jurisdiction(s) and the claim posture because the content and tone should change depending on whether the matter is pre-suit, in suit but pre-discovery, post-discovery, or on the eve of trial. The LLM should ask the user for (and review, if provided) the core claim file materials that will later be used to judge whether the insurer had enough information to reasonably evaluate and accept the demand.\n\nAt a minimum, collect the following: the accident or incident report(s) and any citations; photos, video, scene diagrams, and vehicle or property damage estimates; witness statements and contact details; insured and insurer identifying information, including claim number, policy number (if known), adjuster contact info, and the names of all potentially insured individuals and entities; written confirmation of the available liability policy limits, including any umbrella or excess layers, or a plan to request verification through the policy declarations page or discovery responses; medical records and bills to date (emergency room, imaging, treating providers), prognosis and impairment ratings if available, and any future care estimates; wage loss documentation and employment records if wage loss is claimed; lien information (health insurer, Medicare/Medicaid, ERISA plan, hospital liens, workers' compensation) and what can be represented accurately at this stage; prior settlement communications, including any insurer requests for information and any offers or counteroffers; a draft release concept (who is released, what claims are released, what is reserved), including whether the claimant will release only the insured or also the insurer; and any pending suit pleadings, scheduling orders, trial dates, and mediation dates.\n\nYou must also obtain client-specific constraints that affect settlement mechanics: whether the client needs structured settlement options, whether there are minors or incapacity issues requiring court approval, whether there are multiple claimants competing for the same limits, and whether the client will consider releasing only some insureds. For bodily injury matters, confirm whether the client is willing to provide medical authorizations; if so, define them narrowly to avoid overbroad disclosure and confidentiality concerns. Confirm you have client authorization for the settlement position and release scope, as Model Rule 1.2 reserves settlement decisions to the client.\n\nIf any required information is missing\u2014especially policy limits confirmation, identities of insureds, or medical documentation establishing damages severity\u2014the LLM should stop and ask targeted follow-up questions rather than drafting a \"thin\" demand that invites a \"not enough information\" response. A demand made without sufficient supporting documentation is often legally ineffective to trigger bad faith duties. If the user insists on proceeding with incomplete information, the LLM should draft in a way that makes the offer reasonably evaluable (include available documentation and offer to provide additional records promptly) and should flag the missing pieces as risk points for attorney review.\n\n## 4. Step-by-Step Process\n\n### Step 1: Identify the Governing Bad Faith Framework and Prerequisites\n\nBegin by determining what legal theory this letter is meant to support: common law failure to settle, statutory bad faith, unfair claims practices statute, or some combination. The workflow differs materially depending on the answer. Some jurisdictions require a statutory notice and cure period before a statutory bad faith action may be filed, and that notice may have mandated content and delivery methods. In those states, a time-limited demand may still be useful, but it should be coordinated with (and not inadvertently undermine) statutory prerequisites.\n\nBecause the platform cannot assume a jurisdiction's rules from memory, the LLM must perform web research for the specific state before drafting. Search for: \"[State] third-party bad faith failure to settle elements,\" \"[State] time-limited demand statute,\" \"[State] civil remedy notice bad faith,\" and \"[State] insurer duty to settle within limits standard.\" Any statement about elements, required notices, or cure periods must be either supported with a URL citation to an authoritative source (statutory text, court opinion, regulator guidance) or explicitly flagged for attorney verification. Do not invent \"leading cases\" or quote holdings from memory.\n\nThe letter's deadline, conditions, and warnings should mirror the jurisdiction's expectations for a \"clear opportunity to settle.\" For example, some courts focus on whether the demand was \"reasonably clear\" and \"capable of acceptance,\" while others are more forgiving of minor ambiguities if the insurer could have clarified them. If you impose a very short deadline without justification, you risk creating a record that looks like entrapment. Conversely, a carefully justified deadline (tied to upcoming depositions, mediation, trial setting, or medical cost escalation, or the need to protect the insured from imminent exposure) looks more reasonable.\n\nCommon mistakes include copying another state's statutory notice language into the demand, asserting legal standards as absolutes without verifying them, threatening criminal or disciplinary action to coerce payment, and setting a deadline that cannot practically be met (such as demanding a check and executed release within 72 hours without offering wiring instructions or specifying payees).\n\nAdversarial awareness: insurers and their counsel frequently defend bad faith suits by arguing that the claimant's demand was unclear, contained hidden conditions, required performance beyond the policy, or did not allow a realistic time for internal approvals. Drafting choices here should anticipate that defense and create a clean record that the insurer had a straightforward path to acceptance.\n\n### Step 2: Build an Evidentiary Liability Narrative That Makes Excess Exposure Foreseeable\n\nThe first substantive section of the TLD must demonstrate that liability is clear. A bad faith claim typically cannot be sustained if there is a bona fide dispute regarding who caused the accident. Write a concise but concrete liability narrative: who did what, what rule of the road or duty was breached, what evidence supports it (police report, witness names, photos), and why comparative fault defenses are weak. If liability is contested, acknowledge the dispute honestly but explain why the insured's exposure remains substantial. Use active language and cite specific evidence.\n\nThe point is foreseeability of an excess judgment. Insurers are expected to evaluate settlement in light of verdict risk. A demand that merely says \"your insured is 100% at fault\" without support is easy to discount. Instead, attach key exhibits and cite them in the letter. If you do not have exhibits, explain what you have and offer immediate production while still making the demand evaluable.\n\nIllustrative example: \"Independent witness Jane Smith states your insured ran the red light and struck Ms. Lopez broadside (Ex. B, Smith Statement). The scene photos show your insured's vehicle resting beyond the crosswalk consistent with entering on red (Ex. C). Your insured was cited for [statute] (Ex. A). On these facts, a jury is likely to assign primary fault to your insured.\" Any statutory citation should be verified by web research or flagged for attorney verification.\n\nCommon mistakes include overstating certainty, omitting unfavorable facts that will later surface, and failing to address obvious defenses (seat belt non-use, sudden emergency, prior injuries). A supervising attorney will expect the letter to inoculate against defense arguments: acknowledge material defense points and explain why they do not reduce exposure below limits. In modified comparative negligence jurisdictions, the demand must account for comparative fault rather than ignore it.\n\nAdversarial awareness: the insurer may later claim it lacked sufficient liability clarity to tender limits. Anticipate this by documenting why the existing evidence is enough to recognize substantial risk, by citing evidence already in the insurer's possession, and by offering reasonable cooperation to provide additional information promptly.\n\n### Step 3: Present Damages Tied to Concrete Documentation and a Plausible Verdict Range\n\nExplain damages in the way a claims professional and later a jury would evaluate them: objective injury evidence, treatment timeline, permanency and prognosis, specials (medical bills, wage loss), and non-economic damages anchored in the human impact (pain, limitations, loss of enjoyment). The goal is to show why a reasonable verdict could exceed limits. This is the heart of the bad faith trigger: if the policy is $50,000 and medical bills are $75,000, the case for excess value is straightforward. If the bills are $10,000 but the injury is a permanent facial scar, you must provide jury verdict research showing that similar pain and suffering awards in this jurisdiction consistently exceed the policy limit.\n\nInclude a clean damages summary with numbers that can be verified from the bills attached. Be attentive to jurisdiction-specific rules regarding the proper measure of medical damages (\"billed\" versus \"paid\" amounts). If the numbers are incomplete, say so explicitly and identify what is outstanding. Avoid inflated estimates without support; that undermines credibility.\n\nAddress future damages where appropriate: future surgery recommendation, ongoing therapy, impairment rating, work restrictions, and any life care plan components. If you lack expert support, phrase future care cautiously and attach the medical record. If you have expert reports, summarize them faithfully.\n\nIllustrative example: \"To date, Ms. Lopez has incurred $48,732.19 in medical expenses (Ex. D, itemized billing summary; Ex. E, records). MRI confirms [finding] (Ex. E). Treating physician documents persistent radiculopathy and recommends [treatment] (Ex. F). Ms. Lopez missed 6 weeks of work with wage loss of $7,840 (Ex. G). Under the standard set forth in [State case law], an insurer must consider the total exposure to its insured. Given the surgical intervention recommended and the permanent loss of range of motion, a jury verdict in [County] is reasonably expected to reach $[range], far exceeding the $[limit] policy limit.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include presenting a demand with no medical documentation, failing to separate pre-existing conditions from new injuries, miscalculating specials, and using generic \"multiplier\" rhetoric as though it were an established legal rule. Treat multipliers as negotiation shorthand, not a legal standard.\n\nAdversarial awareness: insurers often argue they could not evaluate damages because records were incomplete or authorizations were withheld. Neutralize that by attaching core records, offering narrowly tailored authorizations, and giving a reasonable window for review.\n\n### Step 4: Craft the Offer to Be Clear, Unequivocal, and Operationally Easy to Accept\n\nThe heart of the letter is the offer. It must be \"clear, unequivocal, and unconditional\"\u2014or as close to unconditional as the circumstances permit. Draft it as a contract: definite terms, clear acceptance mechanism, and a timeline. The offer should specify the amount demanded (typically \"the full and complete liability policy limits\" or a specific sum), identify which policy or policies it applies to, and define what the claimant will provide in exchange (release terms, dismissal with prejudice if in suit, and any lien handling representation). If the offer is contingent on things the insurer cannot control, it may be invalid as a bad faith trigger in some jurisdictions.\n\nIf you are demanding \"policy limits,\" you must handle verification. Prefer language that requires the insurer to confirm limits in writing and tender them. Whether the insurer has a duty to disclose limits varies by state; verify by web research and cite the statute or rule if you assert a duty. If unsure, draft as a request and preserve the point for attorney follow-up.\n\nSettlement mechanics should be practical. Specify payees (client name and trust account), delivery method (overnight to a stated address or wire instructions upon request), and what constitutes timely acceptance (written acceptance by email plus proof of check issuance, for example). Avoid conditions that require third-party actions within the deadline unless you can truly perform them. Instead, use representations and reasonable cooperation clauses.\n\nIllustrative offer language (adapt to jurisdiction and attorney strategy): \"Subject to the terms below, our client will execute a release of [Named Insured(s)] of all bodily injury claims arising from the [date] incident in exchange for tender of the full and complete liability limits of $[Amount] under Policy No. [Number]. Acceptance must be communicated in writing to [email] on or before [date/time/time zone]. Payment must be issued by that deadline and sent via overnight delivery to [address], payable to '[Client] and [Law Firm] Client Trust Account.' Upon receipt of payment, we will promptly provide an executed release and dismissal paperwork (if applicable). Plaintiff will satisfy all valid liens from the settlement proceeds.\"\n\nBe careful with release scope. If there are multiple insureds, multiple vehicles, multiple claimants, or potential product or entity defendants, the release must be tailored so it does not inadvertently release non-settling parties or coverage claims the client intends to preserve. Do not include a release of \"all claims, known or unknown\" without attorney review; some jurisdictions regulate releases of unknown claims (for example, California Civil Code \u00a7 1542 provides a statutory waiver requirement for unknown claims). The release should satisfy the insurer's need for finality without stripping the plaintiff of other potential recoveries such as UIM claims or claims against other tortfeasors.\n\nCommon mistakes include \"acceptance\" that requires the insurer to do something ambiguous; a deadline stated without a time zone; demanding a release that is never attached or described; and including confidentiality or non-disparagement obligations that unnecessarily complicate acceptance.\n\nAdversarial awareness: in later litigation, the insurer will parse whether it accepted \"on time\" and whether the claimant moved the goalposts. Make acceptance criteria objective and measurable, and avoid adding new conditions after the insurer attempts to accept.\n\n### Step 5: Set a Strict but Defensible Deadline and Explain Why the Window Is Reasonable\n\nA deadline that is too short is often deemed a \"legal nullity\" or a \"bad faith set-up\" by the courts\u2014exactly the opposite of what you intend. The deadline must give the insurer a reasonable time to investigate and evaluate the claim. Typically, 21 to 30 days is considered standard, though it can be shorter if the insurer has had the file for months and all information has been previously provided, or longer if the case involves complex multi-party issues. The letter should justify the time window in practical terms: impending litigation deadlines, deposition dates, trial setting, the claimant's ongoing damages and need for resolution, or the risk that settlement posture will change as discovery develops.\n\nSpecify the deadline precisely: date, time, and time zone; how acceptance must be delivered (email and/or fax); and where payment must be sent. State that the offer is withdrawn automatically if not accepted as stated. If you intend any grace period for mail delays, state it; if not, say so.\n\nIllustrative example: \"This offer remains open until 5:00 p.m. Pacific Time on March 15, 2026. Written acceptance must be received by that time at [email]. If acceptance is not received by that time, the offer is withdrawn and will not be renewed on the same terms.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include unrealistic deadlines untethered to any rationale, providing an acceptance method that is hard to comply with (such as only by certified mail), and setting a deadline that falls on a weekend or holiday without clarifying whether it extends to the next business day.\n\nAdversarial awareness: insurers frequently claim internal approval processes prevented timely acceptance. Courts vary on sympathy for that argument. Your job is to give a reasonable window and to invite prompt communication if the insurer needs clarification\u2014then document any failure to engage.\n\n### Step 6: Include Calibrated Bad Faith Framing\n\nThe bad faith portion should read like a professional notice, not a threat. The theme is protection of the insured: the insurer has a chance to eliminate personal exposure by tendering limits. Explicitly state that failure to accept may expose the insured to an excess judgment and that the claimant intends to pursue the full measure of damages. Avoid asserting you \"will\" win or that bad faith liability is automatic; instead, describe the foreseeable consequences.\n\nRemind the insurer of its duty to communicate the demand to the insured so the insured may seek independent counsel regarding personal exposure. This serves both the insured's interests and the evidentiary record.\n\nIllustrative example: \"Given the clear liability evidence and the seriousness and permanence of Ms. Lopez's injuries, there is a substantial likelihood of an excess verdict. This demand provides [Insurer] a reasonable opportunity to protect its insured from personal exposure by tendering limits. Should you elect to reject this offer, or allow it to expire, you do so at your own peril. We will seek the full value of any judgment rendered at trial, including amounts in excess of the policy limit, and will look to your company for payment based on your failure to settle within limits when you had the opportunity to do so. We strongly encourage you to provide a copy of this demand to your insured so they may seek independent counsel regarding their personal exposure. We will document [Insurer]'s response and handling of this settlement opportunity.\"\n\nInvite practical communication: request that the insurer contact you promptly with any questions about documentation, payees, release language, or insured identity. But do not create ambiguity by saying \"we can discuss extensions\" unless you actually intend that. If you are willing to consider a short extension upon good-faith progress, provide a structured mechanism for requesting one.\n\nCommon mistakes include inflammatory accusations of bad faith without foundation, threatening to report the adjuster to regulators as a coercive tactic, and including extraneous rhetoric that antagonizes decision-makers.\n\nAdversarial awareness: hostile tone can become an exhibit used against you. You want the record to show you were reasonable, professional, and cooperative while maintaining a clear deadline and clear terms.\n\n### Step 7: Package the Letter as a Claims-File Exhibit\n\nA well-crafted demand can still fail if it is not delivered and documented properly. Choose delivery methods that you can prove: email with read receipt (if available), certified mail or overnight delivery with tracking, and if the insurer uses an upload portal, upload there as well. Address it to the adjuster, copy the supervisor if known, and if defense counsel has appeared, copy counsel. If the jurisdiction has specific delivery requirements for time-limited demands (for example, Georgia's OCGA \u00a7 9-11-67.1 requires certified mail or statutory overnight delivery), comply with those requirements precisely.\n\nBe mindful of ethical rules regarding communication with represented parties. Communications to the insurer and adjuster are generally permissible, but communications directly to the insured may implicate Model Rule 4.2 (communication with a represented person) and should be attorney-approved.\n\nOrganize exhibits so the adjuster can evaluate quickly. Attach a short index and label each exhibit clearly. Where HIPAA or other privacy concerns apply, minimize sensitive data (such as redacting unrelated diagnoses) unless disclosure is necessary and authorized.\n\nPreserve the record. Save the final PDF, all exhibits, delivery confirmations, and any follow-up communications in a way that can later be authenticated. If your practice uses a demand-tracking log, enter the deadline and follow up before it expires.\n\nCommon mistakes include sending the letter to the wrong carrier address, failing to include the claim number, attaching records without context, and failing to preserve proof of delivery.\n\nAdversarial awareness: in bad faith litigation, the insurer will scrutinize whether it actually received the demand, whether the attachments were legible, and whether the deadline was clear. Treat delivery and documentation as part of the legal substance.\n\n## 5. Critical Legal Standards and Compliance\n\nThis workflow is high-risk because it is designed to influence subsequent extra-contractual litigation. Ethical compliance is therefore central.\n\nCompetence and diligence require legal knowledge, skill, thoroughness, and preparation, and diligent pursuit of client objectives (ABA Model Rules 1.1 and 1.3). Do not draft a jurisdiction-specific bad faith demand without confirming the state's prerequisites and doctrines through reliable sources.\n\nTruthfulness in statements to others: Model Rule 4.1 prohibits making false statements of material fact or law to a third person. Do not misstate policy limits, injuries, medical costs, or legal standards. If something is unknown (such as the existence of an umbrella policy), say it is unknown and request confirmation. Overstating medical bills or concealing a pre-existing injury in a TLD can result in sanctions or a voided bad faith claim.\n\nRespect for rights of third persons: Model Rule 4.4 prohibits using means that have no substantial purpose other than to embarrass, delay, or burden. Avoid personal attacks, threats unrelated to the civil claim, or coercive \"reporting\" threats.\n\nConfidentiality and privacy: Model Rule 1.6 requires protection of client information. In medical-heavy demands, disclose only what is necessary to evaluate the claim and what is authorized by the client. If you provide medical authorizations, narrow them in scope and time.\n\nCandor and later court use: while this letter is not filed with a court, it often becomes evidence. Under Model Rule 3.3 (candor toward the tribunal), any misrepresentations made within the demand can be used to impeach the attorney or the client if the letter is later offered as an exhibit. Avoid statements that could be characterized as misleading or inconsistent with later pleadings.\n\nClient authority to settle: Model Rule 1.2 reserves settlement decisions to the client. Confirm you have client authorization for the settlement position and release scope. Document the client's informed consent regarding policy-limits settlement versus pursuing potential excess recovery.\n\nERISA and Medicare compliance: failure to address how liens will be handled can make the offer \"conditional\" and therefore ineffective to trigger bad faith in some jurisdictions. Federal Medicare Secondary Payer obligations can complicate \"quick tender\" demands. If Medicare is involved, avoid representations that liens are fully resolved within the deadline. Instead, propose escrow or holdback language or cooperation clauses, and have an attorney confirm the compliance strategy.\n\nMalpractice risk areas include creating an unenforceable or ambiguous offer, inadvertently releasing claims against other defendants or insurers, missing statutory notice prerequisites for statutory bad faith, and disclosing protected health information unnecessarily. Mitigate by requiring attorney review, careful release drafting, and verifying the jurisdiction's statutory scheme.\n\nAnti-hallucination guardrail: any citation to state statutes, insurance regulations, or case law must be verified via web search and included with a URL, or explicitly flagged for attorney verification. Do not invent case names, quote holdings from memory, or assert jurisdictional rules without confirming them through current, authoritative sources.\n\n## 6. Quality Control and Review\n\nReview the draft as if it will be attached to a motion for summary judgment in a future bad faith case. Confirm legal accuracy: any statement about duties to settle, disclosure of limits, statutory notice prerequisites, or cure periods must be supported by authoritative sources with URLs or flagged for attorney verification. Confirm factual support: every key factual assertion about liability and damages should be traceable to an exhibit, a client statement (noted as such), or another reliable source. Avoid \"fact-sounding\" conjecture.\n\nApply the \"pop\" test: does the document clearly establish that the purpose is to trigger the insurer's duty to settle within limits? Does it present a demand that an ordinarily prudent insurer would accept to protect its insured?\n\nEvaluate clarity and operability. The insurer should be able to answer \"What must we do, by when, and where do we send it?\" without calling you. Acceptance terms must be internally consistent: same deadline repeated, same time zone, same method. Ensure the release scope is described precisely and does not accidentally release unwanted parties. If you attach a proposed release, ensure it matches the description in the letter.\n\nPerform a documentation check: are all medical bills and records referenced in the text actually attached as exhibits? An insurer cannot be in bad faith for failing to evaluate records it has not seen. Verify mathematical accuracy: do the medical bills and wage loss figures match the records? Discrepancies are used by insurers to justify \"further investigation\" delays.\n\nTest adversarial resilience. Ask how opposing counsel would attack the demand: \"impossible conditions,\" \"short fuse,\" \"missing records,\" \"unclear who is released,\" \"multiple claimants,\" \"lien uncertainty,\" \"deadline ambiguity,\" \"payment logistics.\" Revise to neutralize those arguments while preserving firmness.\n\nIf the jurisdiction has a TLD statute (such as Georgia's OCGA \u00a7 9-11-67.1 or Florida's Fla. Stat. \u00a7 624.155), confirm strict compliance with every single technical requirement, as missing a statutory element can invalidate the entire bad faith trigger.\n\nCitations and exhibits must be accurate and properly labeled. If you summarize records, verify the summary matches the record language. If you quote a medical record, quote exactly and include the page.\n\nFinally, explicitly flag uncertainties for attorney verification: unknown policy layers, disputed insured identity, incomplete medical records, unresolved liens, and any jurisdictional doctrine not confirmed by web research.\n\nAll output from this skill requires attorney review and approval before use. This skill does not provide legal advice and cannot substitute for counsel's judgment about jurisdictional requirements, client objectives, and ethical constraints.\n\n## 7. Jurisdiction-Specific Adaptations\n\nTime-limited demands and bad faith exposure vary dramatically by state. This skill is written as a general workflow and must be adapted based on the governing law verified by web research. What follows are illustrative examples of major jurisdictional variations; they are not exhaustive and must be confirmed through current legal research before reliance.\n\nTexas follows the *Stowers* doctrine. The standard requires that (1) the claim is within the scope of coverage, (2) the amount of the demand is within policy limits, and (3) the terms of the demand are such that an ordinarily prudent insurer would accept it to avoid the risk of an excess judgment. See *G.A. Stowers Furniture Co. v. American Indemnity Co.*, 15 S.W.2d 544 (Tex. Comm'n App. 1929).\n\nCalifornia applies the standard from *Comunale v. Traders & General Insurance Co.*, 50 Cal. 2d 654 (1958), and *Crisci v. Security Insurance Co.*, 66 Cal. 2d 425 (1967). The test is whether a prudent insurer would have accepted the settlement if it alone were to be liable for the entire judgment. California also has specific rules regarding the \"genuineness\" of the time limit and requires that releases of unknown claims comply with Civil Code \u00a7 1542.\n\nGeorgia imposes extremely strict statutory requirements under OCGA \u00a7 9-11-67.1. The demand must be sent via certified mail or statutory overnight delivery. Failure to include a required term can be fatal to the bad faith trigger. The LLM must verify the specific content requirements of this statute before drafting any Georgia TLD.\n\nFlorida has complex statutory provisions under Fla. Stat. \u00a7 624.155 for insurer bad faith, including pre-suit civil remedy notice requirements. The LLM must verify the current status of Florida's bad faith framework, including any changes enacted by recent tort reform legislation (such as HB 837, enacted in 2023), which significantly altered bad faith standards in that state.\n\nStatutory notice states versus common law states: in some jurisdictions, statutory bad faith claims require pre-suit notice to the insurer and a cure period with specific content and service rules. If that applies, coordinate the time-limited demand with the statutory notice. The demand may supply the \"opportunity to cure,\" but the statute may impose different timelines and content. The LLM must not assume the demand letter alone satisfies statutory prerequisites; it must verify and, if necessary, produce a separate statutory notice.\n\nPolicy limits disclosure: some states require insurers to disclose limits upon request; others do not or impose conditions. If the user wants to demand limits disclosure, the LLM must verify the state rule or statute and cite it with a URL.\n\nMultiple claimants and interpleader: in multi-claimant accidents with limited limits, insurers may argue they must investigate competing claims or consider interpleader. In such cases, a time-limited demand must anticipate allocation issues and may need to invite a global resolution conference, demand disclosure of other claims (where permitted), or propose pro-rata settlement. The correct approach is highly jurisdiction-specific and should be attorney-driven.\n\nComparative fault regimes and caps: states differ on comparative negligence, joint and several liability, and damages caps. These differences affect excess exposure and the reasonableness of a limits demand. The LLM should research whether caps or modified comparative fault could realistically bring exposure below limits and should address those defenses if relevant.\n\nIn all jurisdictions, the safest drafting posture is professional clarity: provide enough information to evaluate, make acceptance easy, give a reasonable deadline, and document that the demand's purpose is to protect the insured from excess exposure\u2014while avoiding traps that later look like manufactured bad faith.\n\nThe LLM must always perform a web search for \"[State] Time Limited Demand Statute\" or \"[State] Bad Faith Elements\" before finalizing any demand to ensure compliance with the most recent legislative changes and judicial interpretations.",
